snippet.textDisplay:
Something you never seem to take into account when talking about keyboard layouts like this is that full-size arrow keys are often much more pleasant to use than those with squashed up and down arrow keys, especially when playing games which heavily utilise arrow keys. Smaller up and down arrow keys, compared to full-size ones, are much harder to reliably and quickly press, which can be problematic when playing games like The Binding of Isaac where reliably making quick key-presses is important - the fact that this is a gaming computer makes this even more pertinent.
I understand that the small right shift key is annoying, but I think a lot of people would consider this a reasonable compromise to make.

snippet.textDisplay:
The reason we can't get a truly perfect ultralight gaming laptop is the power supply issue.
When I got my "laptop" that has the two 330w power bricks, I googled around for why they didn't use just 1 bigger brick,
and it turns out power bricks are highly regulated and making 1 larger brick would cost more than double the cost of using two power bricks.
Now, given the 2080 is the only good 4k gaming card, the power draw would require 3 of those power bricks, which aren't portable
or 1 massive brick the size of a backup battery that would cost more than the laptop to make.
While I like the UI scaling with 4k, the screen size and power consumption 4k causes makes 4k less practical.
With 17.3" being the standard "large display size" for gaming laptops and average viewing distance with laptops being 2',
there will be little to no perceivable difference between 4k and 1080p (aside from UI scaling),
all while requiring 4x the horsepower (and putting out much more heat, which is something laptops already struggle with).
Even if money was absolutely no issue, the best you could hope for is something twice as thick as current ultralights,
that would weigh around 25-30lbs with the power brick.
Panel quality matters more for laptops (considering viewing distance and screen size) than higher resolution.
A good 1080p panel will look better in game than a middle tier 4k panel.
I believe these issues are carving a niche for people that want portability on larger external displays (tvs/projectors),
so I wouldn't be surprised to see a 4k ready liquid cooled NUC in the near future.
For now, 4k on a laptop is a complete waste.

snippet.textDisplay:
I see screen tear. A huge problem with laptops that use a NVIDIA GPU is their Optimus technology. The igpu will always handle the display, while the 3D (or hardware accelerated) program will run in a container inside of the discreet GPU. This causes massive screen tear, forcing the use of VSync. This kills performance AND you can say bye bye to competitive shooters and racing games thanks to input latency.
I didn't know this when I bought my ACER VX-591G in summer of 2017. I learned quick though 😂.
Please keep this in mind when shopping this holiday season; ONLY buy laptops that allow you to turn off "Optimus" in the BIOS.
